x4freetext: Tandem accelerator of the ALTO facility
NEutron source) Li7 beam of 15 MeV energy, maximum
polypropylene target discs of 8 cm diameter, 20 microm
Neutron flux up to 10**7 n/sec. Average energy 1.7 MeV.
A neutron flux up to 3*10**5 n/s/cm2 at the target
Two targets of 235U and 238U of around 300 microg/cm2
thickness, 6.5cm diameter were placed back to back at
the central cathode of ionization chamber.
The time of flight technique with the combined
time resolution of the ionization chamber and BaF2
detector being 4.2 ns FWHM - for prompt neutron/gamma
discrimination. Possible for neutrons up to 10 MeV.
Twin Frisch-grid ionization chamber, filled with
P10 counting gas at a pressure of 1.2 atm - for fission
fragments detection. Placed at 15 cm from the neutron
14 hexagonal BaF2 crystals of 10 cm diameter,
14 cm length - for coincident fission gamma rays
232Th, AmBe sources in energy range 121 keV - 4.4 MeV.
Detector responses to monoenergetic photons of energies
between 0 and 10 MeV were obtained via simulating
emission from the 235U and 238U targets at the center
of the ionization chamber for each detector energy bin.
Response matrices were then created from the ensemble
of the resulting simulated detected spectra.
Fitted exponential parameters to the high-energy tails
(above 2 MeV) of emitted prompt fission gamma spectra
Statistical errors are the dominant source of
The systematic error comes from the normalization and
could be as high as 40%. However, this systematic error
cancels when we take the ratio of 235U/238U spectra.
